Hey Nora! A “heartbeat” is just a quick double-blink with a longer pause. Delays are in milliseconds (1000 ms = 1 second).

Quick and simple (Arduino, built-in LED on pin 13):
- 60 BPM example:
  void setup() {
    pinMode(LED_BUILTIN, OUTPUT);
  }
  void loop() {
    digitalWrite(LED_BUILTIN, HIGH); delay(100);  // thump
    digitalWrite(LED_BUILTIN, LOW);  delay(100);  // tiny gap
    digitalWrite(LED_BUILTIN, HIGH); delay(100);  // thump
    digitalWrite(LED_BUILTIN, LOW);  delay(700);  // rest (100+100+100+700 = 1000 ms)
  }

Change the last delay to speed up or slow down:
- Faster (about 75 BPM): make the last delay 500 (total 800 ms).
- Slower (about 50 BPM): make the last delay 1100 (total 1400 ms).

If you want to set an exact BPM:
- One heartbeat cycle length = 60000 / BPM.
- The first three delays add up to 300 ms (100 + 100 + 100), so:
  rest = (60000 / BPM) - 300

Example with a BPM variable:
  const int LED = LED_BUILTIN; // or 13
  int bpm = 72;

  void setup() { pinMode(LED, OUTPUT); }

  void loop() {
    unsigned long cycle = 60000UL / bpm;
    unsigned long rest = (cycle > 300) ? (cycle - 300) : 0;

    digitalWrite(LED, HIGH); delay(100);
    digitalWrite(LED, LOW);  delay(100);
    digitalWrite(LED, HIGH); delay(100);
    digitalWrite(LED, LOW);  delay(rest);
  }

